  <content>
    <title>Terraform Module Security and Testing</title>

    <summary>Terraform modules must never embed secrets, must follow IAM and network least-privilege, and must be tested with terraform validate, terraform test (native), and optionally Terratest before release. A CI/CD pipeline with format check, validation, lint, security scan, plan, and gated apply stages is the minimum quality bar for production modules.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>A Terraform module is infrastructure-as-code: a bug in the module applies to every environment that calls it. Hardcoded secrets in .tf files get committed to Git and leak in state files. Wildcard IAM policies violate the principle of least privilege and create audit failures. Missing encryption settings leave data exposed. Without automated tests, a module regression may not be caught until a production apply fails. A layered CI pipeline (validate → lint → security scan → plan → gated apply) catches errors at the cheapest layer first.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Writing or reviewing a Terraform module that manages IAM, networking, encryption, or secret references.</item>
        <item>Setting up a CI/CD pipeline for a Terraform module or environment.</item>
        <item>Adding tests to an existing module that lacks automated validation.</item>
        <item>Conducting a security review of a module before promoting it to production.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Prototype or throwaway environments — apply a lighter checklist; skip Terratest.</item>
        <item>Read-only modules that only expose data sources — security scan for secrets is still required.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="secrets-management">
      <p>Secrets in Terraform must never be hardcoded in .tf files or .tfvars files committed to Git. The state file is equally sensitive — it stores all resource attributes including those marked sensitive.</p>

      <rules>
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>MUST NOT hardcode secrets, passwords, API keys, or tokens in any .tf file, .tfvars file, or module default value. Secrets MUST be referenced from a secret manager (AWS Secrets Manager, Vault, GCP Secret Manager) or passed as sensitive variables sourced from environment variables or a CI secrets store.</statement>
          <rationale>Git history is permanent. A secret committed and then removed is still recoverable via git log. State files containing sensitive = true attributes must be stored in encrypted backends with access controls.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>The .gitignore of every Terraform project MUST exclude *.tfstate, *.tfstate.*, and *.tfvars files that contain real secrets. terraform.tfvars is excluded by default but project-specific var files must be listed explicitly.</statement>
          <rationale>A state file committed to a public or semi-public repo exposes all resource attributes, including passwords generated by the aws_db_instance resource.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </rules>

      <checklist>
        <check>No secrets in .tf files — verified by tfsec / Checkov secret scan.</check>
        <check>No secrets in .tfvars committed to Git.</check>
        <check>Secrets referenced from secret managers (Vault, AWS Secrets Manager, GCP Secret Manager).</check>
        <check>.gitignore excludes *.tfstate, *.tfvars (if sensitive).</check>
        <check>State backend uses encryption at rest and access-controlled IAM policy.</check>
        <check>Variables containing secrets declare sensitive = true.</check>
        <check>Outputs echoing secret values declare sensitive = true.</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="iam-permissions">
      <p>IAM policies created or referenced by Terraform modules must follow least-privilege. Wildcard permissions are the most common audit finding in Terraform-managed infrastructure.</p>

      <rules>
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>IAM policies in modules MUST NOT use wildcard (*) in the Action field without explicit justification documented in a code comment. Where wildcards are unavoidable (e.g., s3:*Object*), scope them with a Resource ARN condition.</statement>
          <rationale>Wildcard actions grant more permissions than required, violate SOC 2 and ISO 27001 least-privilege controls, and are flagged by Checkov, tfsec, and AWS Security Hub.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>IAM policies MUST be attached to roles, not to IAM users. Modules MUST NOT create IAM user access keys.</statement>
          <rationale>User access keys are long-lived credentials that cannot be rotated automatically. Role-based access uses short-lived STS tokens and supports MFA enforcement.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Resource-level permissions MUST be used wherever the service supports them. MUST NOT use Resource: "*" when a specific ARN pattern is known at module authoring time.</statement>
          <rationale>Resource: "*" on an IAM action grants that action on every resource in the account, not just the ones the module manages.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </rules>

      <checklist>
        <check>Least privilege principle applied to all IAM policies.</check>
        <check>No wildcard (*) actions without justification comment.</check>
        <check>Resource-level permissions used where supported.</check>
        <check>IAM policies attached to roles, not users.</check>
        <check>No IAM user access keys created in modules.</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="network-security">
      <p>Network security groups and firewall rules created by Terraform modules must follow a default-deny posture. Open ingress is the most common misconfiguration caught by security scanners.</p>

      <rules>
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Security group ingress rules MUST NOT use cidr_blocks = ["0.0.0.0/0"] without explicit justification. Public-facing load balancers are the only acceptable exception. All other services must restrict ingress to known CIDR ranges or security group references.</statement>
          <rationale>Open ingress exposes services to the full internet. Even non-authenticated services can be DoS targets. Least-privilege ingress limits the attack surface.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Databases MUST be placed in private subnets. MUST NOT set publicly_accessible = true on RDS instances or assign public IPs to database hosts.</statement>
          <rationale>A publicly accessible database with a weak password is accessible to the internet. Private subnet placement requires a bastion or VPN for access, adding a layer of defense.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </rules>

      <checklist>
        <check>Security groups follow least privilege (no 0.0.0.0/0 ingress without justification).</check>
        <check>Private subnets used for databases and internal services.</check>
        <check>VPC flow logs enabled where required by compliance.</check>
        <check>Encryption at rest enabled for storage resources.</check>
        <check>Encryption in transit enabled (TLS, SSL).</check>
        <check>Logging enabled for audit trails (CloudTrail, Cloud Audit Logs).</check>
        <check>Tags meet organizational requirements (cost center, environment, owner).</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="testing">
      <p>Terraform modules must be validated and tested before release. Three layers of testing exist: static validation (format + validate + tflint), native Terraform tests (terraform test), and integration tests (Terratest).</p>

      <rules>
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Every module MUST pass terraform fmt -check, terraform validate, and tflint on every commit. These checks MUST be enforced in CI before any plan or apply step runs.</statement>
          <rationale>Format check catches style drift that makes diffs hard to review. Validate catches syntax and type errors. tflint catches provider-specific anti-patterns (deprecated arguments, missing required tags).</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Modules with conditional logic (count, for_each, dynamic blocks, conditionals on outputs) MUST have at least one terraform test (.tftest.hcl) that validates the conditional branches.</statement>
          <rationale>Uncovered conditional branches mean a misconfiguration in that branch may not be caught until a production apply.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Security scans MUST be run with Checkov or tfsec on every pull request. A clean scan MUST be a required check before merge. MUST NOT suppress findings without a documented justification in a suppressions file.</statement>
          <rationale>Security findings accumulate quickly if not enforced at the PR gate. Suppression files make exceptions auditable and reviewable.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </rules>

      <example type="good" title="terraform test — vpc creation and validation">
        <code lang="hcl"><![CDATA[
# tests/vpc.tftest.hcl

run "vpc_creation" {
  command = plan

  variables {
    name               = "test"
    vpc_cidr           = "10.0.0.0/16"
    availability_zones = ["us-east-1a", "us-east-1b"]
  }

  assert {
    condition     = aws_vpc.main.cidr_block == "10.0.0.0/16"
    error_message = "VPC CIDR block is incorrect"
  }

  assert {
    condition     = length(aws_subnet.public) == 2
    error_message = "Expected 2 public subnets"
  }
}

run "vpc_validation" {
  command = plan

  variables {
    name               = "test"
    vpc_cidr           = "invalid"
    availability_zones = ["us-east-1a"]
  }

  expect_failures = [var.vpc_cidr]
}
]]></code>
        <note>The second test case verifies that the CIDR validation block fires correctly on invalid input. Without this, the validation block may exist but never actually block bad values.</note>
      </example>

      <checklist>
        <check>terraform fmt runs on save (editor integration) and as pre-commit hook.</check>
        <check>terraform validate in pre-commit hook.</check>
        <check>tflint lint check passes on every commit.</check>
        <check>terraform plan shows expected changes — no unexpected deletions or recreations.</check>
        <check>Unit tests with terraform test for conditional logic branches.</check>
        <check>Integration tests with Terratest for modules with real cloud dependencies (if applicable).</check>
        <check>Security scan with Checkov or tfsec — clean result required before merge.</check>
        <check>Policy check with Sentinel or OPA (if using Terraform Cloud/Enterprise).</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="cicd-pipeline">
      <p>A module CI/CD pipeline must enforce quality gates in order: cheap static checks first, expensive cloud operations last, with a human approval gate before production applies.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>CI pipelines for Terraform MUST run stages in this order: (1) format check, (2) validate, (3) lint (tflint), (4) security scan (Checkov/tfsec), (5) plan (on PR), (6) apply (on main merge, with manual approval for production). Plan MUST NOT run if any earlier stage fails.</statement>
        <rationale>Running plan before security scan wastes CI minutes and allows a malicious or buggy plan to run against a real environment before security issues are surfaced. Cheap static stages gate expensive ones.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="GitHub Actions CI pipeline for Terraform">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
name: Terraform

on:
  push:
    branches: [main]
  pull_request:
    branches: [main]

jobs:
  validate:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - uses: hashicorp/setup-terraform@v3
        with:
          terraform_version: 1.6.0

      - name: Format Check
        run: terraform fmt -check -recursive

      - name: Init
        run: terraform init -backend=false

      - name: Validate
        run: terraform validate

      - name: TFLint
        uses: terraform-linters/setup-tflint@v4
      - run: tflint --init && tflint

  security:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
      - name: Checkov
        uses: bridgecrewio/checkov-action@v12
        with:
          directory: .
          framework: terraform

  plan:
    needs: [validate, security]
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    if: github.event_name == 'pull_request'
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
      - uses: hashicorp/setup-terraform@v3
      - run: terraform init
      - run: terraform plan -out=tfplan
      - uses: actions/upload-artifact@v4
        with:
          name: tfplan
          path: tfplan

  apply:
    needs: [validate, security]
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    if: github.ref == 'refs/heads/main'
    environment: production
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
      - uses: hashicorp/setup-terraform@v3
      - run: terraform init
      - run: terraform apply -auto-approve
]]></code>
        <note>The apply job uses environment: production which triggers a GitHub required reviewer gate before the job runs. The plan job runs only on PRs; apply runs only on main merges.</note>
      </example>

      <checklist>
        <check>Format check (terraform fmt -check) is the first CI stage.</check>
        <check>Validation (terraform validate) runs before lint.</check>
        <check>Lint (tflint) runs before security scan.</check>
        <check>Security scan (checkov/tfsec) runs before plan.</check>
        <check>Plan runs on pull_request with output artifact saved.</check>
        <check>Apply runs only on main branch merge, with manual approval for production.</check>
        <check>Dev environment tested before staging.</check>
        <check>Staging verified before production.</check>
        <check>Rollback procedure documented in runbook.</check>
      </checklist>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Running terraform apply in CI without a manual approval gate for the production environment.</description>
        <reason>An accidental merge to main or a misconfigured plan can destroy production resources without any human review. Always require a human approval step before production applies.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="code-review-flags">
      <p>During code review, specific patterns are red flags that require investigation regardless of whether automated checks pass.</p>

      <checklist>
        <check>No mega-modules (more than 500 lines across all .tf files).</check>
        <check>No provider blocks in child modules.</check>
        <check>No hardcoded AWS account IDs, project IDs, or organization IDs.</check>
        <check>No wildcard IAM permissions without justification comment.</check>
        <check>No missing encryption settings on storage resources.</check>
        <check>No 0.0.0.0/0 ingress rules on non-load-balancer security groups.</check>
        <check>Variables have descriptions and appropriate defaults.</check>
        <check>Outputs are documented and useful to callers.</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

